# Global Epidemiology Multimorbidity (GEM) Microsimulation Model

**Last updated:** June 16, 2026
**Primary author:** Elizabeth Mitchell (ORCID: 0009-0005-7176-7465)
**Institution:** Emory University

## Overview

The Global Epidemiology Multimorbidity (GEM) Microsimulation Model is an individual-level microsimulation framework designed to project the epidemiologic, health, and economic impacts of chronic disease interventions across countries, age groups, and sexes.

The model was developed between 2025 and 2026 and incorporates population, epidemiologic, mortality, disability, and treatment-effect data from publicly available sources, including the United Nations Population Division, Global Burden of Disease (GBD), and NCD-RisC.

The version accompanying the BMJ submission evaluates the potential population health impact of expanded semaglutide access globally.

